{"title":"Exploiting Audio-Visual Consistency with Partial Supervision for Spatial Audio Generation","domain":"MULTIMODAL","seeds":[{"problem":"Converting monaural video audio into binaural (left/right) audio typically requires large datasets with ground-truth binaural recordings, which are costly to collect.","method":"Introduce an audio-visual consistency mechanism that aligns interaural level difference (ILD)-based left/right cues from audio with visually grounded localization. The model computes an audio-only left/right probability from the magnitude difference of predicted left/right spectrograms (|S_L|−|S_R|), and an audio-visual probability via co-attention: cosine-similarity between each spectrogram time-frequency patch and the visual feature map, modulated by learnable left/right weighting functions (W_L, W_R). A binary cross-entropy consistency loss (L_con) matches these probabilities, providing a self-supervised signal that does not require ground-truth binaural labels during training (can also be combined with supervised reconstruction when available)."},{"problem":"Improve spatial audio synthesis quality while reducing reliance on labeled binaural data, and make training effective in both fully supervised and semi-supervised settings.","method":"Embed the proposed consistency module into a U-Net-based spatial audio synthesizer that predicts complex masks (M_L, M_R) to decompose the mono spectrogram into left/right outputs, with visual features injected at the bottleneck. Train with a joint objective: standard binaural reconstruction (or left-right difference) plus the audio-visual consistency loss. This yields state-of-the-art STFT/ENV performance across FAIR-PLAY and processed 360° datasets, and achieves performance comparable to fully supervised baselines using only about 60% of labeled binaural data."}]}
